            "content": "Part I (Hadith 6) <br>23 <br>Hadhrat Ibn Umar (Radhiyallaho anho) narrates that <br>Rasulullah (Sallallaho alaihe wasallam) said, \"Hasad <br>(jealousy) is not permitted except in respect of two <br>persons-one whom Allah blesses with recitation of <br>a = <br>Qur'an and he remains engaged in it day and night, = ar <br>and the other who is given a lot of wealth by Allah and <br>he spends it day and night.\" <br>;$<br>c*<br>On the authority of many ayaat of the Qur'an and nu- <br>g<br>merous ahadith, hasad is an evil and is absolutely forbid- <br>den. This hadith, however appears to permit hasad in <br>respect of two persons. Because there are many well-known <br>traditions dealing with hasad, the Ulama (Plural of aalim- <br>religious scholar) have interpreted this hadith in two ways. <br>Firstly, hasad as denoted by the Arabic word 'ghibtah', is <br>taken here in the sense of emulation. There is a difference <br>between jealousy and emulation. Hasad is a desire that one <br>possessing a blessing should be deprived of it: whether the <br>person who feels jealous acquires it or not, while emu-<br>lation signifies a desire to possess a thing, whether the <br>actual owner is deprived of it or not. Since hasad is haram <br>(religiously unlawful) under Ijma (consensus of opiniod), <br>h<br>Ul<br>h<br>l<br>d b<br>f<br>h<br>hi<br>d"
